{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413770"},"attributes":{"position":26,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:27:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:27:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22371"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569848"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:33:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:33:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22371"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"22371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22371"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.03,0.11,0.1,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15336"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115771"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15336"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22371"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97775"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9326"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41775"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45980"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of intermittent rectal bleeding. The bleeding occurs at the time of defaecation, when he notices a swelling at the anal verge that settles spontaneously when he has finished. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications, apart from stool softeners which have not relieved his symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Proctoscopy reveals a visible haemorrhoid when he strains. A colonoscopy has been performed and is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rubber band ligation","Stapled haemorrhoidectomy","Injection sclerotherapy","Haemorrhoid artery ligation","Excisional haemorrhoidectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with grade II haemorrhoids, characterised by protrusion beyond the anal verge with straining and spontaneous reduction without manual intervention. Haemorrhoids can be classified into the following grades:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI: protrusion into the anal canal, occasional bleeding, but no prolapse\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EII: protrusion beyond the anal verge with straining or defaecation and spontaneous reduction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIII: spontaneous protrusion or as the result of straining, requiring manual reduction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIV: permanent prolapse and unable to be reduced\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of haemorrhoids depends on their grade, symptoms, and patient preference.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhoid artery ligation\u003C/strong\u003E is an appropriate treatment for grade II haemorrhoids. This technique uses Doppler ultrasound to identify and ligate the arterial supply to the haemorrhoidal tissue, reducing blood flow and causing the haemorrhoid to shrink. It is less painful than excisional techniques, has a quicker recovery time, and is particularly effective for grade II-III haemorrhoids with bleeding as the predominant symptom.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERubber band ligation\u003C/strong\u003E is a commonly used office-based procedure for grade I-II haemorrhoids. While effective, it can be associated with significant pain and has a higher recurrence rate compared to artery ligation for grade II haemorrhoids. It involves placing rubber bands around the base of the haemorrhoid, causing it to necrose and slough off. This is the most effective office-based treatment to offer this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInjection sclerotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E involves injecting a sclerosing agent into the submucosa of the haemorrhoid. It is most effective for grade I haemorrhoids and primarily addresses bleeding rather than prolapse. For this patient with grade II haemorrhoids and prolapse, it would be less effective than artery ligation or rubber band ligation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStapled haemorrhoidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E (also called stapled haemorrhoidopexy) is typically reserved for circumferential grade III haemorrhoids. It involves stapling the redundant rectal mucosa and would be overly aggressive for this patient\u0027s grade II haemorrhoids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcisional haemorrhoidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most invasive option and is generally reserved for grade III-IV haemorrhoids or when other treatments have failed. It involves surgical excision of the haemorrhoidal tissue and is associated with significant post-operative pain and longer recovery times. This would be excessive for this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConservative measures should be tried first for grade I-II haemorrhoids, including increased dietary fibre, adequate fluid intake, and avoidance of straining. However, this patient has already tried stool softeners without relief, suggesting that a more interventional approach is now warranted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemorrhoids are classified into four grades based on their degree of prolapse and reducibility.","Haemorrhoid artery ligation is an effective treatment for grade II haemorrhoids with minimal post-operative pain.","Conservative measures should be tried first for grade I-II haemorrhoids before proceeding to interventional treatments.","Rubber band ligation is the most effective office-based treatment for grade II haemorrhoids."],"references":["Hawkins AT, Davis BR, Bhama AR, et al. The American Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids. Dis Colon Rectum. 2024; 67:614-23."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97775"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22371"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97775"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-25T11:14:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-25T11:15:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15336"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115771"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":nul